Garbage collection : Garbage collection (GC) in Java is an automatic memory management process that reclaims memory occupied by objects that are no longer in use by the program.
This allows developers to focus on application logic without manually allocating and deallocating memory.

How Garbage Collection Works :
The Java Virtual Machine (JVM) manages a large memory area called the heap, where objects are created. The garbage collector identifies "dead" (unused/unreachable) objects and removes them to free up space. The basic process usually involves the following steps: 
Marking: The GC identifies all live (reachable) objects in the heap by starting from "GC roots" (e.g., local variables, static variables, active threads) and traversing the object graph. 
Objects not reachable from these roots are considered garbage.
Sweeping: The collector scans the heap and reclaims the memory used by the unmarked (dead) objects.
Compacting: To prevent memory fragmentation, some collectors move the remaining live objects together, creating larger, contiguous blocks of free memory. This makes allocating new objects faster
